Q1:

Recall the advertising data from the last activity; you showed that there was an interaction between age and product type.

library(tidyverse)
library(gsheet)
data <- as_tibble(gsheet2tbl("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/16_HOSmIBDD9oYY1oBQ5Df6eFH9nT6GgO1UWcbMZNLUo/edit?usp=sharing"))
  1. Construct the profile plot for this data.
# mean(data$`A1-P1`) # 22.9
# mean(data$`A1-P2`) # 23.1
# mean(data$`A2-P1`) # 19.6
# mean(data$`A2-P2`) # 30.5
# mean(data$`A3-P1`) # 21.9
# mean(data$`A3-P2`) # 45.6

p1 <- c(22.9, 19.6, 21.9)
p2 <- c(23.1, 30.5, 45.6)
age <- c("5-6", "7-8", "9-10")

graph <- tibble(age, p1, p2)

graph %>% ggplot(aes(x = age, group = 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = p1)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = p2)) + 
  geom_text(aes(x = "9-10", y = 23, label = "Cereal")) +
  geom_text(aes(x = "9-10", y = 46.5, label = "Video Games")) +
  labs(x = "Age Group",
       y = "Average Attention Span (sec)") + 
  theme_bw()

  1. (Challenge!) Perform Tukey’s test to determine which treatment groups are significantly different. Test at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level.
c1 <- data %>% select(`A1-P1`) %>%
  mutate(age = "5-6 years",
         product = "cereal") %>%
  rename(attn = `A1-P1`)
c2 <- data %>% select(`A2-P1`) %>%
  mutate(age = "7-8 years",
         product = "cereal") %>%
  rename(attn = `A2-P1`)
c3 <- data %>% select(`A3-P1`) %>%
  mutate(age = "9-10 years",
         product = "cereal") %>%
  rename(attn = `A3-P1`)
c4 <- data %>% select(`A1-P2`) %>%
  mutate(age = "5-6 years",
         product = "video game") %>%
  rename(attn = `A1-P2`)
c5 <- data %>% select(`A2-P2`) %>%
  mutate(age = "7-8 years",
         product = "video game") %>%
  rename(attn = `A2-P2`)
c6 <- data %>% select(`A3-P2`) %>%
  mutate(age = "9-10 years",
         product = "video game") %>%
  rename(attn = `A3-P2`)
long <- rbind(c1, c2, c3, c4, c5, c6)

m1 <- aov(attn ~ age + product + age:product, data = long)

round(TukeyHSD(m1)$`age:product`, 3)
                                           diff     lwr    upr p adj
7-8 years:cereal-5-6 years:cereal          -3.3 -19.326 12.726 0.990
9-10 years:cereal-5-6 years:cereal         -1.0 -17.026 15.026 1.000
5-6 years:video game-5-6 years:cereal       0.2 -15.826 16.226 1.000
7-8 years:video game-5-6 years:cereal       7.6  -8.426 23.626 0.726
9-10 years:video game-5-6 years:cereal     22.7   6.674 38.726 0.001

9-10 years:video game-7-8 years:cereal     26.0   9.974 42.026 0.000
5-6 years:video game-9-10 years:cereal      1.2 -14.826 17.226 1.000

9-10 years:video game-9-10 years:cereal    23.7   7.674 39.726 0.001
7-8 years:video game-5-6 years:video game   7.4  -8.626 23.426 0.748
9-10 years:video game-5-6 years:video game 22.5   6.474 38.526 0.002
9-10 years:video game-7-8 years:video game 15.1  -0.926 31.126 0.076

Within cereal: - none of the age groups are significantly different (all p > 0.05)

Within video game: - 5-6 years are not different from 7-8 years (p = 0.748) - 5-6 years are different from 9-10 years (p = 0.002) - 7-8 years are not different from 9-10 years (p = 0.076)

Within age groups: - In 5-6 years, there is not a difference between cereal and video games (p > 0.999) - In 7-8 years, there is not a difference between cereal and video games (p = 0.351) - In 9-10 years, there is a difference between cereal and video games (p = 0.001)

  1. Write a short paragraph to explain your results to the advertising researchers.

  2. Graphically assess the ANOVA assumptions – is ANOVA appropriate here?

plot(fitted(m1), resid(m1))

The variance assumption looks okay.

hist(resid(m1))

The histogram looks mostly okay

qqnorm(resid(m1))
qqline(resid(m1))

The qq plot looks okay.

Yes, we have satisfied the ANOVA assumptions.

Q2:

Recall the tomato data from the last activity; you showed that there was not an interaction between shading and phase of growth and that there was at least one main effect.

data <- as_tibble(gsheet2tbl("https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1kUxXje3cTl_PZFQcg8FvESo34UuGNwm1GrKGc4HN0_A/edit?usp=sharing")) %>%
  mutate(PctShade = as.factor(PctShade),
         Phase = as.factor(Phase))
  1. (Challenge!) Construct the profile plot for this data.
# find means
means <- data %>% group_by(Phase, PctShade) %>% summarize(mean = mean(Yield)) %>% ungroup()
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'Phase'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
# separate into individual datasets
early <- means %>% filter(Phase == "Early") %>% rename(Early = mean) %>% select(-Phase)
late <- means %>% filter(Phase == "Late")  %>% rename(Late = mean) %>% select(-Phase)
middle <- means %>% filter(Phase == "Middle") %>% rename(Middle = mean) %>% select(-Phase)

# merge back together
graph <- full_join(early, middle, by = "PctShade")
graph <- full_join(graph, late, by = "PctShade") 

graph %>% ggplot(aes(x = PctShade, group = 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Early), color = "pink") +
  geom_line(aes(y = Middle), color = "blue") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = Late), color = "purple") + 
  geom_text(aes(x = 4.25, y = 66.5, label = "Middle")) +
  geom_text(aes(x = 4.25, y = 64, label = "Late")) +
  geom_text(aes(x = 4.25, y = 55, label = "Early")) +
 labs(x = "Percent of Shade",
      y = "Average Yield") +
  theme_bw()

  1. If there is a main effect of shading, perform Tukey’s test to determine which levels of shading are significantly different. Test at the \(\alpha=0.10\) level.
m2 <- lm(Yield ~ Phase + PctShade, data = data)
anova(m2)

There is a main effect of phase.

m2 <- aov(Yield ~ Phase + PctShade, data = data)
round(TukeyHSD(m2)$Phase, 3)
               diff     lwr   upr p adj
Late-Early    8.326  -1.149 17.80 0.094
Middle-Early  2.462  -7.187 12.11 0.807
Middle-Late  -5.864 -15.339  3.61 0.296

There is only a difference between early and late phases (p = 0.094).

  1. Write a short paragraph to explain your results to the horticulturist.

  2. Graphically assess the ANOVA assumptions – is ANOVA appropriate here?

plot(fitted(m2), resid(m2))

The variance assumption looks okay.

hist(resid(m2))

The histogram looks mostly okay

qqnorm(resid(m2))
qqline(resid(m2))

The qq plot looks okay.

Yes, ANOVA is a valid choice.
